{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640290","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640290"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:14:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:14:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17817"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17817","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17817"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.9,0.03,0.03,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10531"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116764"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10531","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10531"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17817"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98751"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9923"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24575"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24995"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116764","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116764"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECarbon dioxide produced by cellular metabolism must be transported in blood and eventually expelled via the lungs. Most carbon dioxide is carried as bicarbonate ions in plasma.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the formation of bicarbonate ions from carbon dioxide in blood?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Carbon dioxide spontaneously ionises in plasma","Carbon dioxide reacts with water via carbonic anhydrase to form carbonic acid, which dissociates to bicarbonate","Carbon dioxide combines directly with hydroxide ions","Carbon dioxide is converted to bicarbonate by mitochondrial enzymes","Carbon dioxide binds to plasma proteins to form bicarbonate"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe formation of bicarbonate ions occurs through a specific chemical pathway. \u003Cstrong\u003ECarbon dioxide reacts with water via carbonic anhydrase to form carbonic acid, which dissociates to bicarbonate\u003C/strong\u003E. This reaction can be written as:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E + H\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003EO \u21cc H\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003ECO\u003Csub\u003E3\u003C/sub\u003E \u21cc H\u003Csup\u003E+\u003C/sup\u003E + HCO\u003Csub\u003E3\u003C/sub\u003E\u003Csup\u003E-\u003C/sup\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarbon dioxide spontaneously ionises in plasma\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as this process requires enzymatic catalysis and cannot occur spontaneously at a physiologically significant rate. The idea that \u003Cstrong\u003Ecarbon dioxide combines directly with hydroxide ions\u003C/strong\u003E is also incorrect; this reaction requires carbonic anhydrase as a catalyst and cannot occur through direct combination. The conversion of carbon dioxide to bicarbonate occurs primarily in red blood cells and plasma, not within mitochondria, making the option \u003Cstrong\u003Ecarbon dioxide is converted to bicarbonate by mitochondrial enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E incorrect. While some carbon dioxide can bind to proteins, this binding does not result in bicarbonate formation, so \u003Cstrong\u003Ecarbon dioxide binds to plasma proteins to form bicarbonate\u003C/strong\u003E is also incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis reaction is crucial for both pH buffering in blood and the transport of carbon dioxide from tissues to the lungs. The reaction is reversible, allowing bicarbonate to convert back to carbon dioxide in the lungs for expiration.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Carbonic anhydrase catalyses the reversible reaction between carbon dioxide and water to form carbonic acid.","Carbonic acid rapidly dissociates into hydrogen ions and bicarbonate ions.","This reaction is essential for blood pH buffering and carbon dioxide transport in blood."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora GJ, Mellifont R, Derrickson B, Burkett B, Peoples G, D D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition. 2nd ed. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019.","West JB, Luks AM. West\u2019s respiratory physiology: the essentials. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Wolters Kluwer; 2015. Chapter 6; pg. 94."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98751"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17817"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98751","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98751"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-30T15:13:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-30T15:13:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10531"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116764"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"gro